In .NET MAUI, theme detection and control lives on the `Application` class.

### Detect the current theme

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### Subscribe to real-time changes

```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");

    // Update UI or refresh styles here
    ApplyTheme(newTheme);
};
```

### Force a specific theme (override system setting)

```csharp
// Lock to dark mode regardless of device setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Lock to light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

### Putting it together

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Log initial theme
        Debug.WriteLine($"Starting theme: {RequestedTheme}");

        // React to OS-level changes in real time
        RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            Debug.WriteLine($"System theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
            ApplyTheme(e.RequestedTheme);
        };
    }

    public void SetUserOverride(AppTheme theme)
    {
        // AppTheme.Unspecified = follow system
        UserAppTheme = theme;
    }

    private void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        // Swap merged dictionaries, update colors, etc.
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `RequestedTheme` — read-only, reflects the OS setting.
- `UserAppTheme` — writable, overrides the OS setting. Set to `AppTheme.Unspecified` to follow the system again.
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires whenever the **effective** theme changes (OS toggle *or* `UserAppTheme` assignment).
- XAML resources can also react automatically via `AppThemeBinding` (e.g., `{AppThemeBinding Light=#FFF, Dark=#000}`).
